description: {"blocks":[{"key":"27e1v","text":"This is part of the collection DToL Taxon-specific Standard Operating Procedures for the Plant Working Group (protocols.io). The SOP collection contains guidance on how to process the various land plant taxa within the scope of the Darwin Tree of Life project. The guidance specifically refers to the metadata associated with tissue samples for DNA barcoding (which takes place at the Royal Botanic Garden (RBGE)). Every specimen is submitted for DNA barcoding first before potentially being sent to the Wellcome Sanger institute for whole genome sequencing.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":31,"length":92}],"data":{}},{"key":"a95sr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2q49v","text":"This DNA barcoding SOP outlines the processing of plant and lichen sample data for the Darwin Tree of Life project (DToL) at the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh (RBGE). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cjp7u","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d57k0","text":"DNA barcoding is used as part of the species identification process AND sample tracking (to check that the genome sequence corresponds to the material that was sent and that there have been no sample mix-ups).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bms09","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9chgj","text":"Definition: Land plants (Embryophyta) and lichens","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"83q6n","text":"Including: Bryophyta, Marchantiophyta, Anthocerotophyta, Lycopodiophyta, Polypodiophyta, Pinophyta, Cycadophyta, Ginkgophyta, Gnetophyta, Magnoliophyta, lichenized fungi","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":10}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ap94l","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"42dqo","text":"Excluding: all non-lichenized fungi","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"BC757E6696AF11ED921D0A58A9FEAC02","url":"https://www.protocols.io/view/dtol-taxon-specific-standard-operating-procedures-ckvfuw3n/protocols"}}}}

We use our EDNA number as the BOLD sample ID number, while the complete DToL specimen ID number/string of numbers from the barcode-adapted manifest is added into the Notes field. We also include the sample’s major lineage in the Extra Info column, allowing us to sort the project and datasets into broad taxonomic groups (angiosperms, conifers, ferns, lycophytes, mosses, hornworts, liverworts, lichens).","type":"ordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":27,"offset":110,"style":"bold"},{"length":7,"offset":246,"style":"bold"},{"length":9,"offset":255,"style":"bold"},{"length":11,"offset":266,"style":"bold"},{"length":11,"offset":279,"style":"bold"},{"length":7,"offset":292,"style":"bold"},{"length":11,"offset":301,"style":"bold"}],"key":"eb1gr","text":"Once the samples have been uploaded to our BOLD EDToL project, we add them to either our RBGE or RBGK datasets (DS-DTOLRBGE; DS-DTOLRBGK), which team members from the Genome Acquisition Labs have access to, as well as to relevant taxon datasets (DS-FERN, DS-LICHEN, DS-LIVERWRT, DS-LYCOPHYT, DS-MOSS, DS-SEEDPLNT) for ease of analysis. ","type":"ordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":21,"offset":78,"style":"bold"}],"key":"dmuub","text":"After creating them, the samples are downloaded from BOLD in order to get the BOLD ProcessID number that will be needed to upload raw trace files to the BOLD EDTOL project. (BOLD downloads can be saved to the DToL barcode folder on the RBGE DNA server.)","type":"ordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"length":11,"offset":143}],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":11,"offset":143,"style":"UNDERLINE"},{"length":1,"offset":369,"style":"bold"}],"key":"3fmll","text":"After BOLD specimens have been created, photographs of the plants can be uploaded to BOLD in a zipped folder including the Specimen Image form Version 3.0 (download an empty form from the BOLD site) and the images. This has to be completed by the submitting Genome Acquisition Lab (or by the Barcode Hub if the Genome Acquisition Lab submits photos to them along with a Specimen Image form). In order to upload images to BOLD, the submitter needs edit rights to the BOLD EDTOL project, not to the individual Genome Acquisition Lab’s datasets. ","type":"ordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"61cb8","text":"Images should be named in a standard manner, as described in the Collection SOPs, preferably by the collector number as it appears in the manifest, a one-word description, and a number if there are several images in a series, e.g. MR204_flower_1.jpg, MR204_flower_2.jpg; MR204_leaf.jpg, MR204_habitat.jpg. ","type":"ordered-list-item"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"fpng9","text":"Copies of the submitted zipped image folder should be saved, as if there are any problems in the future, e.g. a set of images needing deleted, BOLD will remove the entire submitted batch; it will be important to know exactly what was in the batch in order to resubmit it.
